#Text=Their highest summit Is Mont Lozcre ( about C 510
#Text=Ihet ) . 0 . The Pyrenees form the prlnnipai part of the
#Text=boundary between France and Spain . These moun -
#Text=tains divide the cou . utry into four great basins , the
#Text=form and exposure of which necessarily have a great
#Text=influence on their climate and productions . The nar -
#Text=row valley of the Rhine runs from nortli to < ioutIi ,
#Text=while the open basins of the Seine , the Loire , and the
#Text=Garonne , stretch iu a north - weslt ^ rn direction . The
#Text=Adour rises in the Pyrenees , and washes the walls of
#Text=Bayonne . The other rivers are principally tributa -
#Text=jfes . The Marne and the Oise fall into tne Seine ;
#Text=the Allier , the Loire , the Sarthe , and the Maycnne ,
#Text=into the Loire ; the Rhone receives the Saoue , the
#Text=Isire , the Durance , the Ain , and the Sorgue ; the
#Text=Tarn and the Dordi ^ e join the Garonne . The nu -
#Text=merous branches of these rivers are joined by canals ,
#Text=which form an extensive internal water communication .
#Text=In resprct to soil , the richest part of France is the
#Text=north - west division , comprehending the provinces of
#Text=Flanders , Artuis , Picardy , Normandy , and the Isle
#Text=of France , where there is a deep rich loam ; about
#Text=18 , I 70,51 > 0 acres in extent . The valley of the Ga -
#Text=ronne ia composed of a friable sandy loam , with a
#Text=calcareous mixture , and moisture suthcient for every
#Text=purpose . This district contains 7 ) 054,501 acres . The
#Text=greet valley of Languedoc is extremely prolific , though
#Text=the toil is not so fine as that of the preceding districts .
#Text=The Limarne , a valley of Auvergne , Is considered
#Text=to have one of the finest stjils in the world . It con -
#Text=atsts of beds of earth , said to be twenty feet deep ,
#Text=formed from the deojmposition of soft basalt . The
#Text=calcareous and chalk formations are extensive . Tlie
#Text=chalk provinces are unfruitful in grain , but the genial
#Text=Influence of the sun allows them other riches . The
#Text=calcarroiis loam on the borders of the chalk formation
#Text=is more productive . In Bretagne , Anjou , and Maine ,
#Text=are immense heaths . The lanite $ are J ^ xtensive tracts
#Text=of sandy deserts , producing nothing but broom , heath ,
#Text=and Junipers . The most extensive are the landes of
#Text=Bordeaux , twenty leagues in length by twelve In
#Text=breadth . In the remaining provinces , gravel , or a
#Text=gravelly sand , is the predominating soil . The woods
#Text=and forests are estimated to oover a space of 10,795,000
#Text=acres . The principal are tlioseof Ardennes , Orleans ,
#Text=and For . taincl'leau . The northern and western coasts

#Text=with safety . The harlwurs are therefore tew . On
